\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Digestion Efficiency of 3C Sample
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• Take a 5 µl aliquot of the 3C samples, BEFORE the addition of the restriction
 enzyme.
 Label as UND (undigested genomic DNA control).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
• After the digestion (i.e overnight incubation), take another 5 µl aliquot
 and label as DIG (digested genomic DNA control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Add 500 µl of Proteinase K buffer and 1 µl of 10 mg/ml Proteinase K (20
 µg final) to the control aliquots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Incubate for 30 minutes at 65 ºC (can be performed o/n if procedure is
 conducted in parallel to the 3C methodology).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Equilibrate for a few minutes at 37 ºC, then add 1 µl of 1 mg/ml RNase
 A (2 µg final) and incubate for 2 hours at 37 ºC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Add 500 µl phenol-chloroform, mix vigorously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 Centrifuge for 20 minutes at 13’000rpm, room temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 Transfer the aqueous phase (upper layer) to a new tube and add 50 µl of
 2 M sodium acetate, pH 5.6, then 1 - 1.5 ml of 100 % ethanol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
7.
 Mix and then precipitate DNA in the -20 ºC freezer for > 2 hours.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
8.
 Centrifuge for 25 minutes at 13’000 rpm, 4 ºC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
9.
 Remove the supernatant and add 500 µl of 70 % ethanol.
 Vortex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
10.
 Centrifuge for 25 minutes at 13’000 rpm, 4 ºC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
11.
 Remove the supernatant and air-dry the pellet at room temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few minutes at 37 ºC may decrease the waiting time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
12.
 Re-suspend pellet in 60 µl of water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sample(s) can now be assessed for digestion efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Real-Time PCR quantifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To check digestion efficiencies, use primer pairs that amplify across each
 restriction site of interest (R), for example the For and Rev of restriction
 enzyme site under investigation.
 To correct for differences in the amount of template added to the PCR,
 also PCR-amplify control regions not containing the restriction site of
 interest (use the “internal” primers used for loading adjustments, providing
 that they do not fall within a restriction site).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use the cycle thresholds (Ct values, i.e.
 the number of PCR cycles required to generate a threshold amount of PCR
 product) to calculate the restriction efficiency according to the following
 formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
% Restriction = 100 – 100 / 2[(CtR – CtC)DIG – (CtR – CtC)UND]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideally the restriction efficiency should be above 60 - 70 %, but you should
 aim for >80 %.
 Samples with lower digestion efficiencies should be discarded.
\end_layout

